('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:mcq:79c23b51', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Find \\( \\int x^3 \\,dx \\).", "options": ["\\( \\frac{x^4}{4} + c \\)", "\\( \\frac{x^4}{3} + c \\)", "\\( x^4 + c \\)", "\\( 3x^2 + c \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Increase the power to 4 and divide by 4: \\( \\frac{x^4}{4} + c \\). Dividing by 3 uses the old power; \\( 3x^2 \\) is the derivative, not the integral."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:mcq:e372a986', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Find \\( \\int 6x^2 \\,dx \\).", "options": ["\\( 2x^3 + c \\)", "\\( 3x^3 + c \\)", "\\( 6x^3 + c \\)", "\\( 12x + c \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\\( 6 \\times \\frac{x^3}{3} = 2x^3 \\), so \\( 2x^3 + c \\). \\( 3x^3 \\) comes from dividing by 2 (the old power) instead of 3."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:mcq:155dc8dc', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Find \\( \\int 4 \\,dx \\).", "options": ["\\( 4x + c \\)", "\\( 4 + c \\)", "\\( 2x^2 + c \\)", "\\( 4x \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A constant \\( 4 = 4x^0 \\) integrates to \\( 4x + c \\). Leaving it as \\( 4 \\) forgets to raise the power; \\( 4x \\) forgets the \\( +c \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:mcq:aae366d1', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Why must an indefinite integral include a constant of integration?", "options": ["Differentiating any constant gives 0, so infinitely many functions share one gradient function", "Because integration always adds 1", "Because the power always increases by 1", "Because \\( +c \\) stores the limits of integration that were removed, so the definite value can be recovered later"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Constants vanish when you differentiate, so integrating cannot recover them; \\( +c \\) covers every possibility."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:mcq:7aeb0343', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Find \\( \\int (2x + 5) \\,dx \\).", "options": ["\\( x^2 + 5x + c \\)", "\\( 2x^2 + 5x + c \\)", "\\( x^2 + 5 + c \\)", "\\( 2 + c \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\\( 2x \\to x^2 \\) and the constant \\( 5 \\to 5x \\). Keeping 5 (not \\( 5x \\)) or not halving the \\( 2x \\) are the usual errors."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:mcq:1a7a11b5', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A student integrates \\( \\frac{dy}{dx} = 3x^2 \\) and writes \\( y = x^3 \\). What is missing?", "options": ["The constant of integration, \\( +c \\)", "Nothing — it is complete", "It should be \\( 3x^3 \\), raising the power but keeping the coefficient", "It should be divided by 3 again"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The integral of \\( 3x^2 \\) is \\( x^3 + c \\); an indefinite integral must always carry the \\( +c \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:mcq:fbf75506', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which is the correct rule for \\( \\int k x^n \\,dx \\) (with \\( n \\) a non-negative integer)?", "options": ["\\( \\frac{k x^{n+1}}{n+1} + c \\)", "\\( \\frac{k x^{n-1}}{n-1} + c \\)", "\\( n k x^{n-1} + c \\)", "\\( \\frac{k x^{n}}{n} + c \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Increase the power by 1 and divide by the new power: \\( \\frac{k x^{n+1}}{n+1} + c \\). Reducing the power is differentiation."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:mcq:7fda8ca9', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "To find the equation of a curve from its gradient function you should:", "options": ["Integrate, then use a known point to find \\( c \\)", "Differentiate the gradient function again to get back the equation of the curve", "Substitute \\( x = 0 \\) only", "There is never enough information"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Integrate \\( \\frac{dy}{dx} \\) to get \\( y \\) (with \\( +c \\)), then substitute the given point to find the value of \\( c \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:mcq:282c55a0', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Find \\( \\int x \\,dx \\).", "options": ["\\( \\frac{x^2}{2} + c \\)", "\\( \\frac{x^2}{1} + c \\)", "\\( 1 + c \\)", "\\( 2x + c \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x = x^1 \\to \\frac{x^2}{2} + c \\). \\( x^2 \\) forgets to divide by 2; \\( 1 \\) and \\( 2x \\) are derivatives, not integrals."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:mcq:219248ea', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What is the difference between an indefinite and a definite integral?", "options": ["An indefinite integral has no limits and gives a function (\\( +c \\)); a definite integral has limits and gives a number", "They are exactly the same", "A definite integral has no limits and its answer is a function with \\( +c \\), while an indefinite integral has limits and evaluates to a number", "An indefinite integral gives a single number"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "No limits → a function with \\( +c \\); limits \\( a \\) and \\( b \\) → a number (the \\( +c \\) cancels)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:mcq:b6b7322c', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A curve has \\( \\frac{dy}{dx} = 4x^3 \\) and passes through the origin \\( (0,\\ 0) \\). Find its equation.", "options": ["\\( y = x^4 \\)", "\\( y = x^4 + c \\)", "\\( y = 12x^2 \\)", "\\( y = 4x^4 \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\\( y = x^4 + c \\); substituting \\( (0,0) \\) gives \\( c = 0 \\), so \\( y = x^4 \\). You must use the point to remove \\( c \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:mcq:1a711a6c', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Find \\( \\int (6x^2 - 4x + 1) \\,dx \\).", "options": ["\\( 2x^3 - 2x^2 + x + c \\)", "\\( 6x^3 - 4x^2 + x + c \\)", "\\( 12x - 4 + c \\)", "\\( 2x^3 - 2x^2 + 1 + c \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\\( 6x^2 \\to 2x^3 \\), \\( -4x \\to -2x^2 \\), \\( 1 \\to x \\). \\( 12x - 4 \\) is the derivative; keeping \\( 1 \\) forgets that a constant integrates to a term in \\( x \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:tf:25e4151f', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Integration is the reverse process of differentiation."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Differentiation finds the gradient function; integration works back from it to the original function."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:tf:022b85b9', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "\\( \\int x^4 \\,dx = 4x^3 + c \\)."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "\\( 4x^3 \\) is the derivative of \\( x^4 \\). Integrating gives \\( \\frac{x^5}{5} + c \\) — increase the power and divide."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:tf:cf4a20fd', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Every indefinite integral needs a constant of integration \\( +c \\)."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Constants vanish on differentiating, so integrating cannot recover them; \\( +c \\) stands for all of them."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:tf:23324a22', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "To integrate \\( x^n \\) you increase the power by 1 and divide by the new power."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "\\( \\int x^n \\,dx = \\frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1} + c \\) — the exact reverse of the differentiation rule."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:tf:fd0e50cc', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "\\( \\int 6x^2 \\,dx = 3x^3 + c \\)."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "You divide by the new power 3, not the old power 2: \\( 6 \\times \\frac{x^3}{3} = 2x^3 + c \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:tf:ff4ce9d2', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A definite integral gives a numerical value, not a function."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "A definite integral has limits and evaluates to a number; the \\( +c \\) cancels out."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:tf:1d887673', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "When finding a curve from its gradient function, the final answer can be left as an expression without \\( y = \\)."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "The question asks for the equation of the curve, so it must be written \\( y = \\ldots \\) — a mark is lost otherwise."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:tf:d45de599', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "The integral of the constant 7 with respect to \\( x \\) is \\( 7x + c \\)."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "A constant \\( 7 = 7x^0 \\) integrates to \\( 7x + c \\); differentiating \\( 7x \\) returns 7."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:learn:2be34fc4', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "What is integration, and why is it the reverse of differentiation?", "reading": "<p><strong>Integration</strong> is the <strong>reverse process of differentiation</strong>. Differentiation takes \\( y \\) and finds its gradient function \\( \\frac{dy}{dx} \\); integration starts from the gradient function and works back to \\( y \\).</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li>The symbol is \\( \\int \\), and you write \\( \\int y\\,dx \\) to mean \"integrate \\( y \\) with respect to \\( x \\)\". The \\( dx \\) tells you the variable, and it is part of the notation — never leave it out.</li>\n              <li>Because differentiating \\( x^3 \\) gives \\( 3x^2 \\), integrating \\( 3x^2 \\) must give back \\( x^3 \\) (plus a constant — see below).</li>\n              <li>A quick sanity check on any integral: <strong>differentiate your answer</strong>. If you get back what you started with, the integration is right.</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p>In this qualification you only ever integrate <strong>polynomials</strong> — sums of terms \\( kx^n \\) where \\( n \\) is a non-negative whole number. You never integrate a trig, exponential or log function; those are A-level.</p>", "question": "Differentiating \\( x^5 \\) gives \\( 5x^4 \\). So what is \\( \\int 5x^4\\,dx \\)?", "options": ["\\( x^5 + c \\)", "\\( 20x^3 + c \\)", "\\( 5x^5 + c \\)", "\\( x^4 + c \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Integration reverses differentiation, so integrating \\( 5x^4 \\) takes you back to \\( x^5 \\) (plus a constant of integration)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:learn:79c23b51', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "How do you integrate a power of x?", "reading": "<p>The single rule the whole topic rests on — one you <strong>MUST MEMORISE</strong> (it is <em>not</em> on the formula sheet):</p>\n            <p>\\[ \\int k x^n \\,dx = \\frac{k x^{n+1}}{n+1} + c. \\]</p>\n            <p>In words: <strong>increase the power by 1, then divide by the new power</strong> — and add a constant. (This is the exact opposite of differentiating, where you multiply by the power and reduce it by 1.) Since \\( n \\) is a non-negative integer here, \\( n+1 \\) is never 0, so the division is always safe.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — find \\( \\int 12x^3 \\,dx \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. The power is \\( n = 3 \\). Increase it by 1: \\( x^{3+1} = x^4 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Divide by the new power, 4: \\( \\frac{12x^4}{4} \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Simplify and add the constant: \\( 3x^4 + c \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. So \\[ \\int 12x^3 \\,dx = 3x^4 + c. \\]</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Check by differentiating: \\( \\frac{d}{dx}(3x^4 + c) = 12x^3 \\). ✓</p>", "question": "Find \\( \\int x^3 \\,dx \\).", "options": ["\\( \\frac{x^4}{4} + c \\)", "\\( \\frac{x^4}{3} + c \\)", "\\( x^4 + c \\)", "\\( 3x^2 + c \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Increase the power to 4 and divide by 4: \\( \\frac{x^4}{4} + c \\). Dividing by the old power (3) or forgetting to divide are the usual slips."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:learn:7aeb0343', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "How do you integrate a whole polynomial?", "reading": "<p>Integrate a sum <strong>term by term</strong>, applying the rule to each term. Two extra points:</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li>A <strong>number multiplying</strong> \\( x^n \\) stays as a factor — e.g. \\( \\int 6x^2 \\,dx = 6 \\times \\frac{x^3}{3} = 2x^3 + c \\).</li>\n              <li>A <strong>constant term</strong> such as \\( 4 \\) is really \\( 4x^0 \\), so it integrates to \\( 4x \\). (Check: differentiating \\( 4x \\) gives 4.)</li>\n              <li>You only need <strong>one</strong> constant \\( +c \\) at the end for the whole expression, not one per term.</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — find \\( \\int (6x^2 - 10x + 4) \\,dx \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. \\( 6x^2 \\to 6 \\times \\frac{x^3}{3} = 2x^3 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. \\( -10x \\to -10 \\times \\frac{x^2}{2} = -5x^2 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. \\( 4 \\to 4x \\) (the constant becomes a term in \\( x \\)).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. Add the single constant: \\[ \\int (6x^2 - 10x + 4)\\,dx = 2x^3 - 5x^2 + 4x + c. \\]</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Differentiate to check: \\( \\frac{d}{dx}(2x^3 - 5x^2 + 4x + c) = 6x^2 - 10x + 4 \\). ✓</p>", "question": "Find \\( \\int (2x + 5) \\,dx \\).", "options": ["\\( x^2 + 5x + c \\)", "\\( 2x^2 + 5x + c \\)", "\\( x^2 + 5 + c \\)", "\\( 2 + c \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\\( 2x \\to x^2 \\) and \\( 5 \\to 5x \\), giving \\( x^2 + 5x + c \\). The constant 5 must become \\( 5x \\), not stay as 5."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:learn:a0993f84', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Why does every indefinite integral need + c?", "reading": "<p>When you differentiate, <strong>any constant disappears</strong> — the derivative of \\( 7 \\), of \\( -3 \\) and of \\( 0 \\) are all \\( 0 \\). So working backwards you cannot know what constant was there.</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li>\\( x^2 + 1 \\), \\( x^2 - 5 \\) and \\( x^2 + 100 \\) all differentiate to \\( 2x \\). Integrating \\( 2x \\) could give <em>any</em> of them.</li>\n              <li>We record this \"unknown constant\" as the <strong>constant of integration</strong>, \\( +c \\). It stands for a whole <strong>family</strong> of parallel curves, all with the same gradient function.</li>\n              <li>An integral written <strong>without limits</strong> is called an <strong>indefinite integral</strong>, and it must <em>always</em> carry \\( +c \\). Dropping it is the most common — and most avoidable — lost mark on this topic.</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p>To pin down which member of the family you want, you need one extra piece of information, such as a point the curve passes through (next card).</p>", "question": "Why must an indefinite integral include \\( +c \\)?", "options": ["The derivative of any constant is 0, so many functions share the same gradient function", "Because integration always adds 1", "Because the power increases by 1", "Because \\( +c \\) stores the limits of integration that were removed, so the value can be found later"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Differentiation erases constants, so integrating cannot recover them — \\( +c \\) represents every possible constant."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:learn:56cbde36', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "How do you find the equation of a curve from its gradient function?", "reading": "<p>If you are told the gradient function \\( \\frac{dy}{dx} \\) <strong>and</strong> one point the curve passes through, you can find the exact equation:</p>\n            <ol>\n              <li><strong>Integrate</strong> \\( \\frac{dy}{dx} \\) to get \\( y \\) in terms of \\( x \\) — remember \\( +c \\).</li>\n              <li><strong>Substitute</strong> the known point''s coordinates and solve for \\( c \\).</li>\n              <li><strong>Write the answer as an equation starting \\( y = \\)</strong> — not just an expression.</li>\n            </ol>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — a curve has \\( \\frac{dy}{dx} = 3x^2 - 4x \\) and passes through \\( (2,\\ 1) \\). Find its equation.</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Integrate: \\( y = \\frac{3x^3}{3} - \\frac{4x^2}{2} + c = x^3 - 2x^2 + c \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Substitute \\( (2,\\ 1) \\): \\( 1 = (2)^3 - 2(2)^2 + c = 8 - 8 + c \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. So \\( c = 1 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. The equation is \\[ y = x^3 - 2x^2 + 1. \\]</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Two marks are routinely lost here: forgetting \\( +c \\) (so you can never find it), and giving the final answer as \\( x^3 - 2x^2 + 1 \\) rather than \\( y = x^3 - 2x^2 + 1 \\). The command word is \"equation\", so it <em>must</em> start \\( y = \\).</p>", "question": "A curve has \\( \\frac{dy}{dx} = 4x^3 \\) and passes through the origin. Find \\( y \\).", "options": ["\\( y = x^4 \\)", "\\( y = x^4 + c \\)", "\\( y = 12x^2 \\)", "\\( y = 4x^4 \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\\( y = x^4 + c \\); at \\( (0,0) \\), \\( 0 = 0 + c \\) so \\( c = 0 \\), giving \\( y = x^4 \\). The point is needed to fix the constant."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:learn:625ce32f', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "What is the difference between an indefinite and a definite integral?", "reading": "<p>The two kinds of integral look similar but answer different questions.</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li>An <strong>indefinite integral</strong> \\( \\int y\\,dx \\) has <strong>no limits</strong>. Its answer is a <strong>function</strong> (plus \\( +c \\)) — for example \\( \\int 2x\\,dx = x^2 + c \\). That is the topic of this page.</li>\n              <li>A <strong>definite integral</strong> \\( \\int_a^b y\\,dx \\) has <strong>limits</strong> \\( a \\) and \\( b \\) written on the sign. Its answer is a single <strong>number</strong>, and the constant \\( +c \\) cancels out, so no \\( +c \\) appears. Definite integrals give areas under curves — that is the next lesson (9.2).</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p>So: <strong>no limits → a function with \\( +c \\); limits → a number, no \\( +c \\).</strong> Knowing which one a question wants tells you whether to expect a formula or a value as your answer.</p>", "question": "Which describes an indefinite integral?", "options": ["No limits; the answer is a function including \\( +c \\)", "Limits \\( a \\) and \\( b \\) are given, so the answer is a single number", "It always equals zero", "It never needs \\( +c \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "An indefinite integral has no limits and gives a function plus a constant of integration; a definite integral has limits and gives a number."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:misc:f5558d03', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \\( \\int 3x^2 \\,dx = x^3 \\)</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Every indefinite integral needs the constant of integration. A weak answer stops at \\( x^3 \\); a strong answer writes \\( x^3 + c \\) — and without it you can never find the curve''s equation later.</p>", "question": "Find \\( \\int 3x^2 \\,dx \\).", "options": ["\\( x^3 + c \\)", "\\( x^3 \\)", "\\( 6x + c \\)", "\\( \\frac{x^3}{3} + c \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Integrating \\( 3x^2 \\) gives \\( x^3 \\), and an indefinite integral must include \\( +c \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:misc:79c23b51', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \\( \\int x^3 \\,dx = \\frac{x^3}{3} + c \\)</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> You must increase the power first. A weak answer divides by the old power 3; a strong answer raises the power to 4 and divides by 4: \\( \\frac{x^4}{4} + c \\).</p>", "question": "Find \\( \\int x^3 \\,dx \\).", "options": ["\\( \\frac{x^4}{4} + c \\)", "\\( \\frac{x^3}{3} + c \\)", "\\( 3x^2 + c \\)", "\\( x^4 + c \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Increase the power to 4, then divide by 4: \\( \\frac{x^4}{4} + c \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:misc:7aeb0343', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \\( \\int (2x + 5) \\,dx = x^2 + 5 + c \\)</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> A constant term integrates to a term in \\( x \\). A weak answer keeps the 5; a strong answer writes \\( 5 \\to 5x \\), giving \\( x^2 + 5x + c \\).</p>", "question": "Find \\( \\int (2x + 5) \\,dx \\).", "options": ["\\( x^2 + 5x + c \\)", "\\( x^2 + 5 + c \\)", "\\( 2x^2 + 5x + c \\)", "\\( 2 + c \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\\( 2x \\to x^2 \\) and \\( 5 \\to 5x \\), so \\( x^2 + 5x + c \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:misc:d600bbb7', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Answering ''find the equation of the curve'' with \\( x^3 - 2x^2 + 1 \\)</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The answer must be an equation. A weak answer gives only the expression; a strong answer writes \\( y = x^3 - 2x^2 + 1 \\) — the examiner requires the \\( y = \\).</p>", "question": "How should the equation of a curve be written?", "options": ["Starting with \\( y = \\ldots \\)", "As an expression only", "As \\( \\frac{dy}{dx} = \\ldots \\)", "As a number"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "''Equation of the curve'' means it must be written \\( y = \\ldots \\), not just an expression."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:misc:44b49684', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \\( \\int 4x^2 \\,dx = 8x + c \\)</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> This differentiates instead of integrating. A weak answer multiplies by the power and reduces it; a strong answer increases the power and divides: \\( \\frac{4x^3}{3} + c \\).</p>", "question": "Find \\( \\int 4x^2 \\,dx \\).", "options": ["\\( \\frac{4x^3}{3} + c \\)", "\\( 8x + c \\)", "\\( 4x^3 + c \\)", "\\( \\frac{4x^3}{2} + c \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\\( 4 \\times \\frac{x^3}{3} = \\frac{4x^3}{3} + c \\); \\( 8x \\) is the derivative."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:tips:d09d3675', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Finding a curve: the four-step ladder", "reading": "<p>For \"determine the equation of the curve\" [4], examiners reward four visible steps:</p><p><strong>0 marks:</strong> jump straight to a number, or differentiate by mistake.</p><p><strong>Part marks:</strong> integrate correctly with \\( +c \\) (M1 A1), but forget to use the point, or drop the \\( +c \\) so \\( c \\) cannot be found.</p><p><strong>Full marks:</strong> integrate (with \\( +c \\)), substitute the point to find \\( c \\), then write the final answer as \\( y = \\ldots \\). Show every line so one slip costs one mark, not all four.</p>", "question": "What earns the final mark on ''find the equation of the curve''?", "options": ["Writing the answer as \\( y = \\ldots \\)", "Leaving the answer as an expression", "Giving \\( \\frac{dy}{dx} \\)", "Rounding to 2 d.p."]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The last mark is for the complete equation written \\( y = \\ldots \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:tips:0f23bac4', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Never lose the +c mark", "reading": "<p>The \\( +c \\) is worth a mark in its own right and is the key to finding the constant later. Write \\( +c \\) the moment you integrate — before you even substitute the point. If you drop it, you cannot solve for \\( c \\), and you also lose the accuracy mark for a correct integral.</p>", "question": "When should you write \\( +c \\)?", "options": ["As soon as you integrate an indefinite integral", "Only in definite integrals", "Never", "Only at the very end, and only if the question specifically asks for it"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Add \\( +c \\) immediately on integrating; it is required and lets you find the constant from the point."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration:tips:b3564486', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:9-1-indefinite-integration', '9.1 Indefinite Integration', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "explain — Check by differentiating back", "reading": "<p>Integration and differentiation are opposites, so you can check any integral for free: <strong>differentiate your answer and see if you get the integrand back</strong>. For example, if you claim \\( \\int (6x^2 - 10x + 4)\\,dx = 2x^3 - 5x^2 + 4x + c \\), differentiate the right-hand side: \\( 6x^2 - 10x + 4 \\). ✓ It matches, so the integration is correct.</p>", "question": "How can you check an integral quickly?", "options": ["Differentiate your answer and see if it matches the integrand", "Integrate your answer a second time and check you get the original expression back", "Substitute \\( x = 0 \\)", "You cannot check it"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Because integration reverses differentiation, differentiating a correct integral returns the original expression."}'::jsonb),
